PROBLEM STATEMENT

Use Python (with Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, etc.) to explore the dataset and derive meaningful insights. Your goal is to visualize trends and tell a compelling data story that can help reduce social media addiction among students.

DATA DICTIONARY

STUDENT ID - Id allocated to each student who was included into the survey.

AGE - Age of the student.

GENDER - Gender of the student.

ACADEMIC LEVEL - Academic level of the student.

COUNTRY - Country of the students.

AVG DAILY USAGE HRS - Average daily usage of mobile or mobile applications in hours.

MOST USED PLATFORM - Most used platform by the students.

AFFECTS ACADEMIC PERFORMANCE - Usage of mobile is affecting their performance or not.

SLEEP HOURS PER NIGHT - Sleeping hours per night of individual student.

MENTAL HEALTH SCORE - Mental health score of individual student.

RELATIONSHIP STATUS - Current relationship status of individual student.

CONFLICTS OVER SOCIAL MEDIA - Counts of conflicts over social media.

ADDICTED SCORE - Addiction score of individual student.

3.1 Relationship Between

In[9]:
# AGE, GENDER AND DAILY USAGE IN HOURS
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sns.boxplot(x='Age',y='Avg_Daily_Usage_Hours',data=dataset,hue='Gender')
plt.title("Relationship Between Age,Gender and daily usage")
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above visual, we can see that overally FEMALE users are having more Avg_Daily_Usage_Hrs as compared to MEN, Also It can be seen that the MALE around the age of 21-23 are having more Avg_Daily_Usage_Hrs.

In[10]:
#Sleep patterns, Academic performance, Social interaction
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.catplot(x='Conflicts_Over_Social_Media',y='Sleep_Hours_Per_Night',data=dataset,hue='Affects_Academic_Performance',kind='strip')
plt.title("Relationship Between Sleep,Social Interaction and Academic Performance")
plt.show()

<Figure size 800x500 with 0 Axes>

Conclusion : From the above visual, we can see that students who are having conflicts > 2, are having Affects over their Academic Performance and also Impacting their Sleep_Hours as well.

3.2 Analyze via Demographic

In[11]:
#Analyse how addiction varies demograhically
plt.figure(figsize=(15,20))
country_group=round(dataset.groupby('Country')['Addicted_Score'].mean(),2)
country_sorted=country_group.sort_values(ascending=True)
x=country_sorted.index
y=country_sorted.values
plt.barh(x,y,edgecolor='black',color='#05C1F2',height=0.605)
plt.title("Addiction Demographic",color="#0560F2",weight='bold',size=20)
plt.xlabel("Addiction Score",color="#0560F2",weight='bold',size=20)
plt.ylabel("Countries",color="#0560F2",weight='bold',size=20)
for i in range(len(x)):
    plt.text(y[i]+0.1,x[i],y[i],ha='left',va='center',weight='demi')
plt.xlim(0,10)
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above visual, we can see that the students from countries like [Armenia,Ecuador,Czech Republic,Liechtenstein,Lebanon] are most addicted and students from countries like [Sweden,Slovakia,Japan,Germany] are least addicted

4.Aggregations and Insights

In[12]:
#USE GROUPBY AND AGGREGATIONS TO FIND AVERAGE ADDICTION LEVEL ACCROSS DIFFERENT 
#GENDER

plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
gender_group = dataset.groupby('Gender')['Addicted_Score'].mean().reset_index()
sns.barplot(x='Gender',y='Addicted_Score',data=gender_group,hue='Gender')
plt.title("ADDICTION VS GENDER",color='#A24FF0',weight='bold')
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above plot, we can see that the FEMALE students are MORE Addicted to their phone whereas MALE students are LESS addicted to their phone.

In[13]:
#AGE GROUPS

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
age_grouped = dataset.groupby('Age')['Addicted_Score'].mean().reset_index()

plt.title("ADDICTION VS AGE",color='#A24FF0',weight='bold')
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above plot, we can see that the students of Age:23 are LEAST Addicted to their phone whereas students of Age:18 are addicted MOST to their phone

In[14]:

# Classify risk level (Low/Medium/High) based on usage hours
def Create_risk():
    conditions = [
        (dataset['Addicted_Score'] < 4),
        (dataset['Addicted_Score'] >= 4) & (dataset['Addicted_Score'] < 7),
        (dataset['Addicted_Score'] >= 7)
    ]

    choices = ['Low','Medium','High']

    dataset['Risk_Level'] = np.select(conditions,choices,default='Unknown')
    print(dataset)


print(Create_risk())

# Suggest digital detox strategies using if-else blocks
def process_column(dataset,column_name):
    column_data = dataset[column_name]
    for a in range(len(column_data)):
        if (column_data[a]=='High'):
            print(column_data[a] +" - Full-Day Disconnects: Schedule one full day per week with zero screen time to reset your habits and reconnect offline.")
        elif (column_data[a]=='Medium'):
            print(column_data[a] +" - Scheduled Screen Time: Set fixed time slots for digital use to prevent endless scrolling and regain control.")
        else:
            print(column_data[a] +" - Mindful Scrolling: Practice intentional usepause before opening an app and ask yourself why you're doing it.")
digital_detox = process_column(dataset, 'Risk_Level')
print(digital_detox)

In[26]:
# PAIR PLOT JUST TO KNOW WHAT ALL NUMERICAL DATA WE CAN CONSIDER FOR CHART PREPARATIONS. 
sns.pairplot(data=dataset)
plt.show()
In[21]:
# 1st CHART TO COMPARE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN MENTAL HEALTH AND SLEEP HOURS. 
sns.catplot(x='Mental_Health_Score',y='Sleep_Hours_Per_Night',data=dataset,kind='swarm',size=3,color='#600273')
plt.title("Mental health vs Sleep Hours",color='#0B80F4')
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above plot, we can see that the Mental Health Score of students have increased as their Sleep hours are increased.

In[22]:
#2nd CHART TO COMPARE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN MENTAL HEALTH AND RISK LEVEL. 
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
sns.violinplot(y='Mental_Health_Score',x='Risk_Level',data=dataset,hue='Risk_Level',legend=True)
plt.title("Mental health vs Risk Level",color='#0B80F4')
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above plot, we can see that the ADDICTED RISK_LEVEL is INDIRECTLY PROPORTIONAL TO MENTAL HEALTH SCORE. Meaning those students who are at LOW risk are in good Mental Health, whereas those who are at HIGH rish are having bad Mental Health.

In[23]:
# 3rd CHART TO COMPARE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN ADDICTION AND STUDENT DATA
Std_count = dataset.groupby('Risk_Level')['Student_ID'].count()
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.pie(Std_count.values,labels=Std_count.index,autopct='%.2f%%',pctdistance=0.5,labeldistance=0.7)
plt.title('Addiction wise Total Student data',color='#0B80F4')
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above plot, we can see that the MORE than half population is HIGHLY Addicted, and less than 3% of students are LOW on addiction.

In[24]:
# 4th CHART TO COMPARE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN ADDICTION AND STUDENT DATA
pt2=pd.pivot_table(index='Risk_Level',columns='Most_Used_Platform',values='Addicted_Score',data=dataset)
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
sns.heatmap(pt2,annot=True,cmap='plasma',vmin=2,vmax=8)
plt.title("Application Addiction Matrix",color='#0B80F4')
plt.show()

Conclusion : From the above plot, we can categorise application which are HIGHLY addictive [FACEBOOK, YOUTUBE, INSTAGRAM] and the applications which are LEAST Addictive [LINKEDIN,LINE,TWITTER].

7. Storytelling Deliverable

7.1 Key Patterns

Key Patterns observed for addictions are as follows: -
1. Students, whose mental scores are lower, are more likely to be highly addicted to mobile addiction.
2. Students, as per their relationship status, use the applications, and likewise, they get addicted to those applications.
3. Students, as they officially cross 18+ to access the application's full version, then they are getting more addicted to the same at their initial stage

7.2 Root Causes

Root Causes for such Addiction are as follows: -
1. Lack of Education and Awareness - We need to organise more sessions on how to be digitally productive and not digitally addicted.
2. Lack of self-control - We need to include a curriculum, which helps students with increasing their will-power, self-control, and more mindful exercises
3. Session for parents - We need to organise sessions for parents, wherein they will be educated on how to track their children's digital addiction and help them with their issues

7.3 Recommended Actions to Combat Addiction

High Addiction Level
Full-Day Disconnects: Schedule one full day per week with zero screen time to reset your habits and reconnect offline.
App Blockers & Accountability: Use app blockers and share your goals with a friend or coach to stay accountable and reduce compulsive use.
Medium Addiction Level
Tech-Free Mornings: Avoid screens for the first hour after waking to build mindful routines and reduce dopamine spikes.
Scheduled Screen Time: Set fixed time slots for digital use to prevent endless scrolling and regain control.
Low Addiction Level
Digital Sabbaths: Take short breaks (e.g., Sunday evenings) to reflect, journal, or enjoy nature without devices.
Mindful Scrolling: Practice intentional usepause before opening an app and ask yourself why you're doing it.
****OVERALLY WE CAN FOLLOW THE BELOW ACTIONS, IRRESPECTIVE OF OUR ADDICTION LEVEL****
Mindful Activities: You can perform breath awareness, mindful walking, and gratitude journaling
Meditation: You can meditate, focus on breath, early in the morning to start your day energetically.
Yoga/Exercise: It will keep your Body fit, which will help you to keep your Mind Healthy
UTILISE TIME TO DO PRODUCTIVE ACTIVITIES, BEING OFF THE SCREEN. WHEN ON SCREEN, UTILISE THE APPLICATIONS FOR YOUR GOOD
